A system is linear if it satisfies:

1. **Homogeneity**: T{ax(t)} = aT{x(t)}
2. **Additivity**: T{x₁(t) + x₂(t)} = T{x₁(t)} + T{x₂(t)}

Combined: T{ax₁(t) + bx₂(t)} = aT{x₁(t)} + bT{x₂(t)} (superposition)

1. Compute input spectrum: X(ω) = F{x(t)}
2. Multiply by frequency response: Y(ω) = X(ω)·H(ω)
3. Inverse transform: y(t) = F⁻¹{Y(ω)}

This is often easier than time-domain convolution.
